revision.text:
{{italic title}}
'''''Kitāb al–Milal wa al-Nihal''''' ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]:كتاب الملل والنحل, ''The Book of Sects and Creeds''), written by the [[Islamic scholar]] [[Muhammad al-Shahrastani]] (d. 1153 [[Common Era|CE]]), is a non-polemical study of religious communities and philosophies that had existed up to his time, considered to be the first systematic [[religious studies|study of religion]]. It was written around 1127-1128 and divides religions between sects, which have written doctrines, and creeds which do not.

A French translation of the book by Gimaret, Monnot and Jolivet was sponsored by [[UNESCO]] (''Livre des religions et des sects.'' Leuven, Peeters: vol. I, 1986, Vol. II, 1993).

