{{Infobox artwork | title = Fontes Tamarici | image_file = La Reana2.jpg | caption = | painting_alignment = landscape | alt = | other_language_1 = Spanish | other_title_1 = Fuentes Tamáricas | artist = | year = {{start date|1st century BC}} | type = Public fountain, oracle | material = Stone | subject = | height_metric = 4.5 | length_metric = | width_metric = 2 | metric_unit = m | imperial_unit = ft<!--don't leave blank—either don't include it, or include the default in. --> | condition = | city = [[Velilla del Río Carrión]], [[province of Palencia|Palencia]], [[Spain]] | museum = | accession = | coordinates = {{Coord|42|49|24|N|4|50|45|W|type:landmark_region:IT|display=inline,title}} | owner = | url = <!--{{URL|example.com}} Only for official web pages--> }}
The '''Fontes Tamarici''', in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] ''Fuentes Tamáricas'' ([[English language|English]]: ''Tamaric Fountains'') are three nearby [[Spring (hydrology)|springs]] located by the geographer and Roman historian [[Pliny the Elder]] in [[cantabri|classical Cantabria]], and since the 18th century are being identified with the source of ''La Reana'' in [[Velilla del Río Carrión]] ([[province of Palencia|Palencia]]), [[Spain]]. The first news of the spring, by Pliny, dating from the time of the [[Cantabrian Wars|Roman conquest]] of [[Cantabria]], it has the peculiarity that water emanating from the earth, and its intermittence was considered [[omen]] at this time.<ref>Santa María la Real ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=vkvVGmldTVYC&dq=fuentes+tam%C3%A1ricas+plinio+el+viejo&hl=es&source=gbs_navlinks_s Todo el románico de Palencia''] (2015). {{ISBN|8415072406}}, p. 132.</ref>
== History == It is known that the tamarics [[cantabri]] was who inhabited the area from the 3rd century BC. They worshiped waters and the sacred springs. It is not known the exact year of its construction, but it is clear that when the [[Roman Empire]] conquered [[Cantabria]] (year 19 BC), they found these sources that drew wide attention. The outbreak irregular emptying its waters and unexpected, accompanied by the noise that precedes underground filling, had to be at that time matter of respect and adoration. Possibly they were used as [[Thermae|baths]], [[laundry]] and [[omen]].<ref>Torres Martínez, Juan. ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=KmF4i8PgawwC&dq=fuentes+tam%C3%A1ricas+augurio&hl=es&source=gbs_navlinks_s El Cantábrico en la Edad del Hierro: medioambiente, economía, territorio y sociedad]''. Real Academia de la Historia (2011). {{ISBN|8415069286}}, p. 463</ref> It has been also suggested that the fountain could be dedicated to a god of the waters, where predictions were made based on their irregular filling and emptying cycle. In the thirteenth century it was built beside a [[Hermitage (religious retreat)|hermitage]] devoted to [[John the Baptist]], to Christianize the place and delete all relations with [[pagan]] rites.<ref>Palencia Turismo [http://www.palenciaturismo.es/contenido/ec1eeded-d5f4-11de-b283-fb9baaa14523?seccion=fc27d943-d5f4-11de-b283-fb9baaa14523 Velilla del Río Carrión]. Retrieved 23-04-2016</ref>
== The ''curse'' of Pliny ==
[[File:Arco original.jpg|thumb|250px|Detail of the original [[arch]] still preserved. The other two were rebuilt in the 1980s.]] Studies of the [[naturalist]] and [[geographer]] [[Pliny the Elder]] on the lands occupied by the [[Roman Empire]] are crucial for knowledge and location of Tamaric Fountains. In his ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Naturalis Historiae]]'', XXXI, 3, is where he alludes its particularity:
{{Quote|''Tamaric Fountains, in Cantabria serves as omen. They are three, to eight feet of distance. They come together in one bed, each carrying a large flow. Usually dry for twelve days and sometimes up to twenty, leaving no sign of water, while another adjoining source still flowing without interruption and in abundance. It's bad luck try to see them when they run, as happened recently has the legacy Lartius Licinius, who, after his praetorship, he went to see them when they run dry, and he died seven days later.|author=Pliny the Elder|source= Naturalis historia, XXXI, 23}}
[[Lartius Licinius]] was a great supporter of the work of Pliny, with his intense desire for knowledge of new discoveries, he visited the spring when it were in their dry phase, and died a week after in 70 AD.<ref>Pliny XXXI 24: «sicut proxime Lartio Licinio legato post praeturam; post septem enim dies occidit».</ref>
