[[File:Samye16.JPG|thumb|right|Kurukullā at [[Samye]]]]
[[File:Kurukulla sculpture from Calcutta Art gallery 1913 (2).jpg|thumb|Kurukulla sculpture from Calcutta Art gallery, 1913]]
'''Kurukullā'''  ({{bo|t=ཀུ་རུ་ཀུ་ལླཱ་}}; also {{bo|t=རིག་བྱེད་མ་|w=rig byed ma}} "Knowledge/magic/[[vidyā]] Woman",<ref name="Shaw2006">{{cite book|last=Shaw|first=Miranda|authorlink=Miranda Shaw|title=Buddhist Goddesses of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MvDKOK1h3zMC&pg=PA444|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=0-691-12758-1|page=444}}</ref> {{zh|c=咕嚕咕列佛母}} "Mother-[[Buddhahood|Buddha]] Kuru[kullā]"  or {{zh|c=作明佛母}} "Knowledge-Causing Mother-Buddha"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tibet-lahr.de/vajrakilaya-heruka-dakini/43-vajrakilaya/45-weisheitsdakinis.html |title=Dakinis-Energie und Weisheit |language=de |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719213508/http://www.tibet-lahr.de/vajrakilaya-heruka-dakini/43-vajrakilaya/45-weisheitsdakinis.html |archivedate=2013-07-19 |df= }}</ref>) is a female, peaceful to semi-wrathful [[Vajrayana#Yidam|Yidam]] in [[Tibetan Buddhism]] particularly associated with rites of magnetization<ref name="DTC2011"/> or enchantment. Her Sanskrit name is of unclear origin.<ref name="Shaw2006"/>

==Representation==
Kurukullā is a goddess whose body is usually depicted in red with four arms, holding a bow and arrow made of flowers in one pair of hands and a hook and noose of flowers in the other pair. She dances in a [[Dakini]]-pose and crushes the [[asura]] [[Rahu]] (the one who devours the sun). According to [[Hindu astrology]], Rahu is a snake with a demon head ([[Navagraha]]) who represents the ascending [[lunar node]].

She is considered either an [[emanation]] of [[Amitābha]], one of [[Tara (Buddhism)|Tara]]'s forms, or a transformation of [[Heruka]].

==History==
Kurukullā was likely an Indian tribal deity associated with magical domination. She was assimilated into the Buddhist pantheon at least as early as the ''[[Hevajra Tantra]]'', which contains her [[mantra]]. Her function in Tibetan Buddhism is the "red" function of subjugation. Her root tantra is the ''Arya-tara-kurukulle-kalpa'' (''Practices of the Noble Tara Kurukullā'').<ref name="DTC2011">Dharmachakra Translation Committee (2011)</ref> It was translated by [[Ts'ütr'im jeya]], a disciple of [[Atiśa]].<ref>Beyer (1978), p. 302</ref>

==Mantra==
[[File:Kurukulla_Mantra.svg|thumb|right|The mantra of Kurukulla]]

The essential mantra of Kurukullā is ''Oṁ Kurukulle Hrīḥ Svāhā''  ({{bo|t=ༀ་ཀུ་རུ་ཀུ་ལླེ་ཧྲཱིཿསྭཱ་ཧཱ }}). This mantra uses the vocative form (Kurukulle) of her name.

