{{primary sources|date=December 2011}} {{buddhism}} This is a '''list of sanghas in San Diego County, California''', which corresponds to the ''[[San Diego metropolitan area|San Diego-Carlsbad-San Marcos Metropolitan Statistical Area]]''. All major branches of Buddhism, [[Theravada]], [[Mahayana]], and [[Vajrayana]], are represented there, as is the Mahayana form [[Zen]],<ref name="Warth" /> as are ''[[Vipassanā]]'' and [[Jōdo Shinshū]] ([[Pure Land Buddhism|Pure Land]]). There is also a [[secularity|secular]] Zen sangha. The area is home to [[Monastery#Buddhism|monasteries]] as well as to less formally engaged groups who gather for meditation and community. [[Gautama Buddha|Siddhārtha Gautama]] died over 2500 years ago, but the oldest Buddhist organization in San Diego County is less than 100 years old.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Rapson, Edward James|title=The Cambridge History of India|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TcooAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA156|page=156|publisher=Univ. Pr.|year=1922|accessdate=October 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=Estes />
==History== During 1916, Japanese immigrant Buddhist farmers were killed when what was then named [[Savage Dam|Otay Dam]] gave way and resulted in the Hatfield Flood. The local [[Japanese diaspora]] needed a place to hold religious services and went on to found what they call the oldest Buddhist organization in San Diego County.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Partners|url=http://www.jaclsandiego.org/our-partners/|publisher=Japanese American Citizens League|accessdate=November 4, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Mellin, Maribeth, Jane Onstott, and Judith C. Devlin|title=Insiders' Guide to San Diego|duplicate_url=|edition=6|publisher=Globe Pequot via Google Books|year=2009|isbn=978-0-7627-4870-9|page=333|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rjP8UMPX2fwC&pg=PA333}}</ref> They met informally until they were able to afford a temple space. First they rented a second-floor room on 6th and Market in May 1926.<ref name=Estes /> Boys and girls in costume paraded through downtown to celebrate.<ref name=Estes /> Later, in 1931, they dedicated today's Buddhist Temple of San Diego at 2929 Market.<ref name=Estes>{{cite journal|author=Estes, Donald H.|title=Before the War: Japanese in San Diego|date=Fall 1978|volume=24|issue=4|url=http://www.sandiegohistory.org/journal/78fall/before.htm|journal=The Journal of San Diego History|publisher=San Diego History Center|accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>
